{"text": "=X\n\nnmAnmPmn(7.37)\n\nIn the example above we denote the basis matrices as fPz;S+;S\u0000;P\u0000zg. In general we use the notation Pmn=jnihmj.\n\nNote thatPn=Pnnare projectors, while the n6=moperators are not even hermitian, and therefore cannot be\n\ninterpreted as representing observables.\n\nInstead of using the standard basis fPz;S+;S\u0000;P\u0000zgit is possibly more physically illuminating to take f1;^\u001bx;^\u001by;^\u001bzg\n\nas the basis set. Optionally one can take f1;^Px;^Py;^Pzgorf^Pz;^P\u0000z;^Px;^Pygas the basis set.\n\n39\n\nThe bottom line is that the operators that act on an Ndimensional Hilbert space form an N2dimensional space. We\n\ncan span this space in the standard basis, but physically it is more illuminating, and always possible, to pick a basis\n\nset ofN2hermitian operators. Optionally we can pick a complete set of N2linearly independent projectors. The\n\nlinear relations between sets of states (as implied by the\n\nrst postulate of quantum mechanics) translate into linear\n\nrelations between sets of operators. One should be careful not to abuse the latter statement: in the above example\n\nthe projectorsfPx;Py;Pzgare linearly independent, while the associated states fjxi;jyi;jzigare not.\n\n= = = = = = [7.9] The tomography of quantum states\n\nThe\n\nrst postulate of Quantum Mechanics implies that with any observable we can associate an Hermitian operator\n\nthat belongs to the N2-dimensional space of operators. We can span the whole space of observables by any set of\n\nN2independent operators ^Pr. The standard basis is not physically illuminating, because the matrices Pmnare not\n\nhermitian, and therefore cannot be associated with random variables.", "embedding": [-0.0028886662, -0.032924157, 0.06481414, -0.051857278, -0.005393189, -0.039710987, -0.042145997, -0.0026400834, -0.06619752, 0.055565167, 0.084515505, -0.004407456, -0.006941203, 0.009601013, -0.022090847, -0.01207621, -0.003406738, -0.014748119, -0.048908